# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1908-chicago-cubs-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1871 Chicago White Stockings season** was the second season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at Union Base-Ball Grounds.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] With the debut of the first professional baseball league, the National Association, the Chicago franchise joined up as the "White Stockings." The team went 19–9 and finished second in the league standings.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Pitcher George Zettlein started all 28 of Chicago's games and led the NA with a 2.73 earned run average.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] Near the end of the season, the team lost its stadiums and equipment when the Great Chicago Fire hit the city.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team was able to finish out the season on the road, but had to drop out of the league while the city attempted to recover.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1871-chicago-white-stockings-season] The team would not resurface until 1874.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1874 Chicago White Stockings season** was the third season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the second in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the first at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings returned to the league in 1874 after taking two years to recover from the chaos of the Great Chicago Fire.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They opened their season on Wednesday May 13 hosting the Philadelphia Athletics and shut them out 4 to 0.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1874-chicago-white-stockings-season] They finished fifth in the National Association with a record of 28–31.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1874-major-league-baseball-season] The following are the baseball events of the year 1874 throughout the world.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1875 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fourth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the third and final in the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players and the second at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1875-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished sixth in the National Association with a record of 30–37–2.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] The **1877 Boston Red Caps season** was the seventh season of the franchise.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] Arthur Soden became the new owner of the franchise, who won their first National League pennant.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1877 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 6th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the 2nd in the National League and the fourth at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fifth in the National League with a record of 26–33.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] The **1908 Chicago Cubs season** was the 37th season of the Chicago Cubs franchise, the 33rd in the National League, and the 16th at West Side Park.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] It involved the Cubs winning their third consecutive National League pennant, as well as the World Series for the second consecutive year.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] This team included four future Hall of Famers: manager / first baseman Frank Chance, second baseman Johnny Evers, shortstop Joe Tinker, and pitcher Mordecai Brown.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] In 1908, Brown finished second in the NL in wins and earned run average.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] This would be the last World Series victory for the Cubs until 2016; it would also take until 2003 – an MLB and North American professional sports record of 95 years – for the Cubs to win their next playoff series.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs started the season in Cincinnati.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Orval Overall was the Cubs' Opening Day starting pitcher.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Overall gave up five hits and committed an error in the first inning as the Reds took a 5–0 lead.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs tied the game in the sixth and won the game in the ninth.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Cubs pinch hitter Heinie Zimmerman drove in Johnny Evers.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Mordecai "Three Finger" Brown pitched in the ninth and got a save for the Cubs.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Owner Charles Murphy had added several new seats to the stadium.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Long-time Cub player-manager Cap Anson threw out the first pitch.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Tinker, Evers, and Chance turned their second double play of the season as the Cubs beat the Reds by a score of 7–3.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] On June 30, the Pittsburgh Pirates took first place, as the Cubs lost to the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Starting on July 2, the Pirates started a critical five game series against the Cubs.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] In the first game, Three Finger Brown threw a six hit, no walk shutout, winning the game 3–0.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] On September 26, starting pitcher Ed Reulbach became the only pitcher in Major League Baseball history to pitch two shutouts on the same day.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] That day, the Cubs played a doubleheader against the Brooklyn Dodgers.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Reulbach pitched both games to completion, which the Cubs won by scores of 5–0 and 3–0.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] In the bottom of the 9th inning, Merkle came to bat with two outs and the score tied 1–1.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] At the time, Moose McCormick was on first base.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Merkle singled, and McCormick advanced to third.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Al Bridwell followed with another single, and McCormick trotted home to score the apparent winning run.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] The New York fans in attendance, under the impression that the game was over, ran onto the field to celebrate.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Meanwhile, Merkle, thinking the game was over, ran to the Giants' clubhouse without touching second base (a gesture that was common at the time).
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Cubs second baseman Johnny Evers noticed this, and after retrieving a ball and touching second base, he appealed to umpire Hank O'Day to call Merkle out.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Since Merkle had not touched the base, the umpire called him out on a force play, and McCormick's run did not count.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] The run was therefore nullified, the Giants' victory erased, and the score of the game remained tied.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] Unfortunately, the thousands of fans on the field (as well as the growing darkness in the days before large electric light rigs made night games possible) prevented resumption of the game, and the game was declared a tie.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] The Giants and the Cubs would end the season tied for first place and would have a rematch at the Polo Grounds on October 8.
[src:1908-chicago-cubs-season/1908-chicago-cubs-season] The Cubs won this makeup game, 4–2, and thus the National League pennant.
